post_text:
MESSAGES FROM STAFF

We asked staff what they would like to tell parents as we prepare for the start of school. Here are some of their responses:

- We are working hard to do the very best for your child! Providing them the education they deserve while keeping them safe is our top priority.

- We miss your kids!

- We consider it an honor that you are trusting your child to us during this scary time.

- Stay positive and reassure your kids that whether they are remote or hybrid learners, we will take care of them!

- Teachers didn't want school to be this way either, no one does. We would love for it to be back to "normal".

- Expectations are high.

- Learning will be different than last spring, but it may not be perfect. Please give us grace.

- Safety precautions must be taken seriously by students (at school and home).

- We need families to be on board with what we are doing to teach their children.

post_text:
PARA SAIL YOUR WAY TO A NEW PASSION!

Do you love helping children learn? Do you enjoy providing help to others that truly makes a positive difference in their lives? Our paraeducators do this every school day in a job that can be extremely rewarding and satisfying.

Auburn-Washburn USD 437 is currently looking for additional paraeducators to support student learning in schools. As we reopen schools our paraeducators will play a vital role in supporting both in person and remote learning. You can view our current openings and apply at: http://usd437.net/careers/positions-available/

This is a fantastic way to get involved in the school district and education. You may find along the way that you discover a new passion for a career in education!

To learn more about working at Auburn-Washburn please view our careers page at: http://usd437.net/careers/

post_text:
CLEAN THE WAY TO YOUR PASSION!

Are you the kind of person that enjoys keeping things neat, clean, and organized? Helping maintain a clean and safe learning environment can be an extremely rewarding job that makes a positive difference in the lives of students and their learning every day. The level of cleanliness in a school positively affects a student’s ability to learn AND reduces the spread of germs and disease.

Auburn-Washburn USD 437 is currently looking for additional school custodians to support cleanliness and student learning. As we reopen schools custodians will play a vital role in supporting both in person and remote learning. You can view our current openings and apply at: http://usd437.net/careers/positions-available/

This is yet another great way to be involved in the school district. You may find along the way that you discover a new passion for a career in the custodial profession!

To learn more about working at Auburn-Washburn please view our careers page at: http://usd437.net/careers/

Meal Distribution Changing July 1

Beginning Wednesday, July 1, grab and go meal distribution will continue ONLY at Pauline Central.

- Pauline Central (6625 SW Westview Rd) – 10:30 am-Noon

We want to express our appreciation once again to all the Food Service staff who have been working to provide daily meals since schools closed in March.

Meals for Friday, July 3 will be distributed on July 2. There will be no distribution on Friday, July 3 in observance of the July 4 Holiday. The program at Pauline Central will continue through July 28 (food supplies and staffing permitting).

On July 9 and 23 the Topeka Shawnee County Public Library will be at Pauline Central to give away summer reading resources during the meal distribution.

Meal Distribution Reminders

There will be no meal distributions on Memorial Day, Monday, May 25. Meals for Memorial Day will be distributed on Friday, May 22.

Beginning Tuesday, May 26, the distribution time at Pauline Central will change to 10:30 am-Noon.

The Auburn-Washburn Child Nutrition staff are currently providing grab and go meals on weekdays at the following drive-up locations:

- Washburn Rural High School (5900 SW 61st St) – 10:30 am-Noon
- Auburn Elementary (810 N Commercial St, Auburn) – 10:30 am-Noon
- Pauline Central (6625 SW Westview Rd) – 9:00-10:30 am (10:30 am-Noon starting Tuesday, May 26)

Distribution will continue at all three sites through June 30 (food supplies and staffing permitting).

Beginning July 1, meal distribution will only take place at Pauline Central. Adjustments to the process may be implemented at that time.

The program at Pauline Central will continue through July 28 (food supplies and staffing permitting).

Meals for Friday, July 3 will be distributed on July 2. There will be no distribution on Friday, July 3 in observance of the July 4 Holiday.

Update on Friday, May 1 Meal Distribution

There will be no meal distribution at any of the three Auburn-Washburn meal distribution sites on Friday, May 1. Distributions on Thursday, April 30 will contain meals for two days. Regular Monday through Friday distributions will resume on Monday, May 4.

The grab and go meals are available free of charge to any child age 1 to 18. Adults can pick up the meals without the children present.

The Auburn-Washburn Food Service staff are providing grab and go meals on weekdays at the following drive-up locations:

- Washburn Rural High School (5900 SW 61st St) – 10:30 am-Noon
- Auburn Elementary (810 N Commercial St, Auburn) – 10:30 am-Noon
- Pauline Central (6625 SW Westview Rd) – 9:00-10:30 am

The Auburn-Washburn Transportation Department staff will be delivering packaged meals from Harvesters on Friday, May 8. The meals would normally be sent home with students for the weekend. Instead they will be delivered to homes of students in the program every other Friday.

Important Message for all Grade 5-12 Band, Orchestra, and Choir Families

USD 437 Music Students and Families,

We ask all of you to make time the week of May 4th to turn in district instruments, music, folders, and formal wear (tuxes, etc). This is for 5th-12th grade families.

Turn in will be at the high school band room. The entrance is right off 61st Street and will be clearly marked with cones. We ask you drop equipment at the curb and do not enter the building. District staff will have to maintain social distancing and wear PPE while handling this process. Times for drop off are:

Monday, May 4: 7:30-8:30am; 11:30am-12:30pm; or 5-6pm

Tuesday, May 5: SAME

Wednesday, May 6: SAME

If none of these times work, please email me at chaffluk@usd437.net with your name, child's name, and school. We will work to accommodate you. Know that we MUST have all equipment back by 6pm Wednesday. Vendors will be arriving to perform summer repair and dry-cleaning services.

Thank you so much,
Luke Chaffee

- Washburn Rural High School – 10:30 am-Noon
- Auburn Elementary (810 N Commercial St, Auburn) – 10:30 am-Noon
- Pauline Central (6625 SW Westview Rd) – 9:00-10:30 am

The grab and go meals are available free of charge to any child age 1 to 18. Adults can pick up the meals without the children present.

post_text:
Horizon Award

Last week Washburn Rural High School German teacher Kaylee Barber was recognized at the KEEN Conference for her Horizon Award.

Kansas Exemplary Educators Network (KEEN) is a network of accomplished and award-winning teachers developed by the Kansas State Department of Education. The KEEN’s mission is to build and utilize a network of exemplary educators who are leaders in the improvement of schools, student performance, and the teaching/education profession.

Earlier this year Kaylee received news of her Horizon Award in a surprise phone call from Kansas Education Commissioner Dr. Randy Watson. Congratulations Kaylee!

post_text: Students Experience Live Art Performance
shared_text:
Auburn-Washburn Public Schools Foundation
February 11 at 3:53 PM ·

Students Experience Live Art Performance

On Tuesday, Live Art Performance Painter Mike Dubus created two large works of art in front of the entire student body at Washburn Rural Middle School. Dubus is an accomplished artist from Kansas City who programs his painting around music and dance to have a fun approach to live painting. When painting for a live audience, Mike has a turning easel that allows him to spin his work and for it to be somewhat of a puzzle for the audience until the painting is nearly completed. The completed paintings will serve as artwork for the school. The event is made possible by a grant from the Auburn-Washburn Public Schools Foundation. More info on Mike Dubus at michaeldebus.com.

Washburn Rural Middle School Language Arts Teacher Lara McDonald was a finalist for Kansas Teacher of the Year. On Kansas Day they visited the Capitol.
shared_text:
Kansas Teacher of the Year Team
January 29 at 9:04 PM ·

Our third day in Topeka was the biggest yet! We got to spend Kansas Day in the capital, speaking to the Senate and House Education Committees and being honored on both the floor of the House of Representatives and the floor of the Senate! We got a standing ovation in both places and felt so very loved. We are proud to represent the 35,000 amazing educators in Kansas! Happy Kansas Day! 🌻❤️

Strategic Planning Feedback Session Set for Wednesday

We are currently seeking feedback from parents about the school district’s next Five-Year Strategic Plan. Your voice is extremely important and we want to hear from you. Please visit www.surveymonkey.com/r/AWSP26 to open an online survey containing five questions being asked to help us create our next Strategic Plan that will guide our work with students from 2021–2026. Thank you, in advance, for completing this survey!

If you would prefer attending a meeting to discuss strategic planning, please remember a meeting has been scheduled for parents this Wednesday evening, 6:00 pm, located at the Shuler Education Center in the Board of Education Room (5928 SW 53rd Street, Topeka).

To learn more about the process visit usd437.net/superintendent/strategic-plan.html.

post_text: Veterans Day Ceremony at Pauline South
text: Veterans Day Ceremony at Pauline South

post_text:
Congratulations!

Congratulations to students Megan Christensen and Meredith Kucera for earning a Discovery Award from the Lowell Milken Center for Unsung Heroes. The award was for a documentary produced last year while Megan and Meredith were at Washburn Rural Middle School. The documentary is about American missionary Carl Wilkens, who chose to stay during the Rwandan Genocide. Megan and Meredith received a $2,000 prize as part of the award. More information and the winning documentary can be found at www.lowellmilkencenter.org/competitions/discovery-award/entry/carl-wilkens.

Congratulations also to Lindsey Dowell, who was one of Megan and Meredith’s teachers at WRMS. Lindsey was named 2019 Kansas Council for History Education Secondary Teacher of the Year.

All three are pictured here with Superintendent Dr. Scott McWilliams and Board of Education President Tom Bruno when they were recognized recently at a Board of Education meeting.

Make A Difference Club Partners with Let's Help Topeka

PLEASE help Washburn Rural MIddle School's MAD club and our new partner, "Let's Help Topeka."

We are beyond excited to pair up with @letshelptopeka for our year of giving. We are both committed to making a difference in our community! We will be working with this incredible local organization all year!

This month (November), we need gently used, CLEAN: Coats, hats, gloves, scarves, socks, and blankets.

Next month (December), anything that is gently used and can be given as a holiday gift to babies, children, teens, and adults.

You can bring items to Mrs. McDonald and Mrs. Katie Jones at WRMS, drop them off at the WRMS commons, or at our District Office.

♥️

THANK YOU!

post_text: Farley Student Wins a Drawing Contest
shared_text:
Farley Elementary School
November 1, 2019 at 10:16 AM ·

Farley Student Wins a Drawing Contest

The Kansas Department of Transportation and the Kansas Highway patrol presented a Farley a 3rd grade student the a first place prize for a drawing contest a Friday morning. The student drew an amazing picture for a poster contest that helps make the public aware of driving safety. The student drew a picture of what could happen if a person drives while texting. The picture showed a car that had run into a school bus. The student received a variety of great prizes including a bike, and $200 for Farley Elementary! Congratulations to this amazing Farley Fox!

post_text:
First Friday Student Art Show

Grade K-12 Art on Display – 5:00-8:00 PM @ Shuler Education Center, 5928 SW 53rd Street

Grade 9-12 Art on Display – 4:00-7:00 PM @ WRHS Library, 5900 SW 61st Street

On Friday, November 1 the community is invited to come and view artwork from hundreds of Auburn Washburn's student artists. Students have created art that gives a Voice to the Voiceless of this world.

At Shuler Education Center artists will be featured in a 'glow' gallery that shines brightly under black lights. There will be refreshments and an opportunity to create a piece of art that that will be part of a display at the office for the remainder of the school year.

Additional high school student work will be on display in the library at Washburn Rural High School.

Everyone is welcome to come celebrate our students and their artwork. The show is part of the district’s 11th annual Cultural Heritage study project that is funded in part by the Auburn-Washburn Public Schools Foundation.

post_text:
Presenters Wanted

Auburn-Washburn is looking for presenters for the 3rd annual AWEsome (Auburn-Washburn Excellence) Conference for staff that will be held on October 25, 2019.

This conference is designed to offer our Classified Staff (office, custodial, transportation, grounds, operations, paraprofessionals, food service, tech support, and others) a morning of professional learning on a wide variety of topics that go beyond the typical mandatory and job-specific training that is routinely offered.

The topics vary each year and run the gamut of Life Skills, Wellness, Technical Skills, Student Support, and more. Sessions are 45 minutes long and you may choose your preferred time(s): 9:10-9:55 am, 10:05-10:50 am, or 11:15-noon.

If you have a motivating and engaging presentation that you would like to share with our staff, please contact Therese Brink Edgecomb at Shuler Education Center with your ideas at edgecthe@usd437.net.

Please, no presentations that are solicitations or sales pitches in nature.

post_text:
Auburn-Washburn has made a small adjustment to the 2019-2020 student calendar that will shift one day when students attend school. School will NOT be in session on Monday, January 6, 2020 as originally planned. School WILL be in session on Monday, April 13, 2020. That day had originally been reserved as a Snow Make-Up day if needed.

The calendar changes were made to accommodate a shift in a professional development training day for teachers. The change was part of the negotiated agreement between the district and teachers that was approved by the Board of Education on August 19, 2019.

We understand that due to the late change some families may have already made plans where their student would not be able to attend on April 13. If that is the case, the absence on that day would be excused. We apologize for any inconvenience this change may cause.

The calendars posted on www.usd437.net have all been updated to reflect the changes.

- Pens/Pencils
- Sharpies
- 3 Ring Binders
- Plastic folders with 3 hole punches
- BACKPACKS
- Highlighters
- Graph paper
- Pen/pencil cases

THANK YOU!

post_text:
Ready for School!

Over a dozen officers from the Kansas Highway Patrol spent part of their morning inspecting Auburn-Washburn buses to ensure they are safe are ready for the start of school. We passed with flying colors.

Beneficial enhancements are coming to the Auburn-Washburn Transportation Department sometime this fall. We will be implementing an upgraded computer routing and student tracking system. This will eventually give parents real-time access to bus scheduling and arrival information. Watch for more details during the fall semester.

Have you ever wondered what it is like to drive one of our big yellow school buses? We are offering just this opportunity by sponsoring The School Bus Driving Experience! Come on out and take a test drive on a controlled course.

WHEN:
Wednesday, July 31 & Thursday, August 1
7:30 AM – 1:00 PM & 4:00 PM – 7:00 PM

The School Bus Driving Experience will be held in the east parking lot of Washburn Rural High School.

The issue has been resolved.

Thank you to all who assisted.
shared_text:
Auburn-Washburn USD 437 Police
July 12, 2019 at 1:49 PM ·

Good afternoon,

I would like to thank the public for their help in resolving an issue we posted about this week in regards to an incident on June 29th. Thanks to your overwhelming support, we were able to identify the individuals in the pictures and made contact with them today.

Initially we took a theft report of items in the area where the individuals were seen. After speaking to them, we determined that it was a misunderstanding and no actual crime occurred. The original post has been removed.

Again, thank you for all your help. We appreciate it and value the partnership we have with the community.

-Chief Ralston

Bus Drivers Earn Top State Honors

The Board of Education recently recognized a group of Auburn-Washburn Bus Drivers who earned several awards at the Kansas School Bus Safety Competition. Driver James Haug won the top state award and qualified to compete in the 49th Annual School Bus Driver International Safety Competition to be held on July 21st, 2019 in Austin, Texas.

Top district award winners included Stephanie Bell - 3rd place at Regional Competition, Anna Cooper - 2nd place State in the Conventional Bus category, James Haug - 1st place State in the Conventional Bus category; 1st place overall, and Benjamin Rickel - Skills test winner in Spot the Dollar (this event requires a driver to stop completely covering a dollar bill sized marker with their passenger rear inside dual tire.

Pictured (l to r) Board of Education President Tom Bruno, Transportation Supervisor Michael Lopez, Safety Coordinator Stephanie Bell, Route Planner Anna Cooper, Driver James Haug, Driver Jaren Thompson, Driver Benjamin Rickel, Driver Rodney Falley, and Superintendent Dr. Scott McWilliams.

All Star Appreciation

The Auburn-Washburn Board of Education recently presented their All Star Appreciation Award to two district staff members. Special Education Data Manager Paula Manteuffel and Wellbeing & Benefits Coordinator Shannon Elwell were recognized for their work. The award is presented as a way to highlight staff members who represent all the great employees working in the district. Congratulations to Paula and Shannon!

post_text:
National History Day Qualifier Recognized

This week the Auburn-Washburn Board of Education recognized another district student who qualified for the National History Day competition to be held in Washington DC this month. Wanamaker Elementary student Max Kuhlmann qualified in Individual Performance with "How the Tragedy of the Apollo 1 Fire Resulted in the Triumphant Apollo 11 Moon Landing." Max is pictured here with Superintendent Dr. Scott McWilliams and Board of Education President Tom Bruno.

Others from Auburn-Washburn who qualified include WRMS students Megan Christensen, Meredith Kucera, Evander Davis, Annika Peterson, Sriya Puvvada, and WRHS student Nicholas Navarro.

Student Wins Congressional Art Competition

Congratulations to Washburn Rural High School Junior Sunny Chen. She won the Kansas Congressional Art Competition. Her art will hang in the tunnel that leads to the Capitol in Washington DC for a year. She is representing the 2nd district of Kansas. Her winning work is titled "Whispers" and the medium is charcoal.

Auburn Elementary students celebrated reading today! Thank you to the Auburn Elementary team for stressing the importance of reading!
